\begin_layout Abstract
We implement and apply the combination of three-dimensional reference interactio
n site model (3D-RISM) with self-consistent field quantum mechanics (SCF
 QM) calculation, in which the electrostatic potential (ESP) induced by
 the solute is directly derived from its electron density.
 The accuracy of the calculation of solvation free energy for neutral solutes
 is analyzed, of which the mainly determining factor is confirmed as the
 solute cavity formation effect.
 Another contribution from the solute electronic structure relaxation in
 aqueous medium, which is possibly induced by the hydrogen bond between
 solute and water solvent, also has noticeable influence on the results
 of SCF QM/3D-RISM calculation.
 By applying the partial molar volume (PMV) correction, our hybrid model
 shows results in good agreement with experiment and a polarizable continuum
 model (PCM), while in the latter the hydrogen bond effect is missing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
3D-RISM, electron density, SCF, partial molar volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment of an aqueous solution can completely change the products,
 mechanism and rate of a given chemical reaction.
 Therefore, its modelling is of central importance of understanding many
 chemical reactions of organic and inorganic species as well as for industrial
 applications.
 Example of pertinent application fields are catalytic reactions like hydrogen
 production, CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 conversion, biomass conversion, or solution chemistry of actinides, which
 is important for radioactive waste disposal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To support current experimental efforts in various areas of catalysis and
 materials science in aqueous media, computational studies are needed to
 examine/predict species and processes at the atomic level.
 One of the two most popular strategies in computational chemistry to study
 solution systems is the combination of quantum mechanics (QM) calculations
 with implicit solvation models, for example, polarizable continuum model
 (PCM) and its variant based the conductor-like solvation model (COSMO).
 Although implicit solvation models have been applied to various chemical
 processes in solution, they provide no insight into the structure and statistic
al fluctuations of the solvent.
 Another type of model is the so-called explicit solvation model, which
 includes the hybrid method between QM calculation and molecular mechanics
 (MM) description of the solvent medium (QM/MM method), and the more accurate
 approach by directly performing molecular dynamics (MD) simulation from
 first principle (ab initio MD, shorthanded as AIMD).
 However, the results of statistical sampling in QM/MM method are only as
 good as the effective force field used to parameterize the solvent-solvent
 and solute-solvent interactions, and the polarizability of the solvent
 medium has to be taken into account to compete with continuum models in
 reproducing electrostatic interactions.
 Also, the statistical sampling of large numbers of solvent configurations
 entails significant computational cost to the combination of QM and MM
 calculations.
 For that same reason, more accurate QM dynamic simulations are restricted
 to a comparably small number of solvent molecules due to their very high
 computational demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the difficulties mentioned above, strategies which combine QM methods
 with integral equation theory of molecular liquids are regarded as a promising
 direction to study ions and complexes and their chemical reactions in aqueous
 solution with sufficient accuracy and at affordable cost.
 One successful approach of this type is the reference interaction site
 model (RISM) which provides solvation energies and also averaged solvent
 structures via site-site radial distribution functions (RDF).
 The hybrid approach of one dimensional (1D) RISM with self-consistent field
 (SCF) QM calculation was first proposed by Ten-no, Hirata and Kato on the
 basis of a variational method to Hartree-Fock equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tenno93"

\end_inset

.
 However, RDFs in 1D-RISM are radial symmetric and dependent only on the
 distance between interaction sites.
 To take into account the solvent structure information presented in three
 dimensional (3D) space around the solute molecule, Kovalenko and Hirata
 combined the Kohn-Sham density functional theory (KS-DFT) with 3D-RISM
 to investigate the electronic structure for a metal--water interface 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

.
 Until now, many implementations have been made to combine RISM theory with
 state-of-the-art QM method to provide researchers an alternative approach
 for classical implicit and explicit solvation models to study chemical
 reactions and processes in solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the hybridization of 3D-RISM with ab inito molecular orbital
 theory was carried out by Sato et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato00"

\end_inset

 for solvation effect on carbon monoxide in aqueous solution.
 Later Du and Wei 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Du03"

\end_inset

 independently combined 3D-RISM equation with hypernetted chain (HNC) closure
 with Gaussian 94 package to study the solvation and polarization of the
 N-methyl amine molecule in aqueous solution.
 Gusarov et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gusarov06"

\end_inset

 also reported their implementation of 3D-RISM with Amsterdam Density Functional
 (ADF) package with analytical gradients, and later applied to study solvation
 effect on conformational equilibria, tautomerization energies and activation
 barriers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Casanova07"

\end_inset

.
 A most recent combination of Gaussian (Gaussian 03) with 3D-RISM was carried
 out by Kloss et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kloss08"

\end_inset

 via an embedded cluster (EC) approach, and applied to the reaction free
 energy for the gauche--trans equilibrium and pKa shift calculations.
 The latest release of NWChem Package.
 To investigate the solvent effects on the electronic structure of solvated
 large-molecular system, Yoshida et al.
 proposed the combination of 3D-RISM with the QM/MM procedure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yoshida11"

\end_inset

 as well as with the fragment molecular orbital (FMO) method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yoshida14"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the numerous implementations, most current hybrid methods of RISM
 with QM calculation construct the electrostatic potential (ESP) induced
 by QM solute with atomic charge fitted from solute electron density.
 However, it is not sufficient to describe the ESP generated by fitted charge
 only 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Minezawa07"

\end_inset

, and more problems would emerge from the existence of a buried atom in
 the system, without saying that the choice for the grid set for fitting
 process has influence on the accuracy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yokogawa07,Sato13"

\end_inset

.
 To obtain more realistic Coulomb interactions, Yokogawa et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yokogawa07"

\end_inset

 proposed the second generation of RISM-SCF theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato13"

\end_inset

, in which the spatial electron density distribution (SEDD) of QM solute
 is included in the RISM-SCF calculation (RISM-SCF-SEDD), by utilizing the
 auxiliary basis set (ABSs) at each atom following the procedure of Gill
 et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gill92"

\end_inset

.
 At the same time, Minezawa et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Minezawa07"

\end_inset

 also reported their 3D-RISM-SCF implementation in which the ESP map on
 a 3D grid is constructed directly from the electron density.
 In this article, we proposed a new method to derive ESP directly from the
 real-space electron density of KS-DFT orbitals, and combine it with the
 parallel code ParaGauss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ParaGaussV3.1"

\end_inset

.
 By utilizing the soft-core pseudopotentials, our hybrid method provides
 an alternative approach for accurate and robust implementation for 3D-RISM-SCF
 implementation, which could be extended to other QM code by coupling the
 real-space representation of solute with 3D RISM solvent medium via an
 convenient interface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that the solvation free energy calculated from 3D-RISM
 overestimates the energy of forming cavity for solute, which is problematic
 especially for neutral ones, since their solvation free energy values are
 around several kcal/mol.
 The possible correction strategies include the repulsive bridge correction
 (RBC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kovalenko00a,book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

 term, cavity formation energy correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Truchon14"

\end_inset

 term and polar molar volume (PMV) correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Palmer10,Sergiievskyi14"

\end_inset

 term.
 In this paper, we applied the most recently reported PMV correction term
 with 3D-RISM while the ESP of solutes are represented with four different
 strategies: (1) The EPS of solutes are derived from the atomic partial
 charges assigned on each solute site, which are also tabulated in standard
 force field database as the LJ parameters in a MM manner; (2) By replacing
 the atomic charge as frozen electron density (FED) which is determined
 from gas-phase QM calculation, solving the solvent correlation functions
 from 3D-RISM equation; (3) QM solute is perturbed by the solvent field
 obtained from MM/3D-RISM; (4) The combination of (2) and (3), in which
 the solvent correlation functions and solute electronic structures are
 determined in the self consistent field (SCF) QM calculation.
\end_layout

