\begin_layout Subsection
3D-RISM theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detailed aspects of 3D-RISM theory have been thoroughly discussed in
 previous work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Sato13,Kovalenko99a,Kovalenko00b,book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 thus here we shortly go through the fundamental formulas in the theory.
 The solute-solvent 3D-RISM integral equation has the following convolution
 form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h^{uv}=c^{uv}\ast\chi^{v}.\label{eq:rism-uv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{uv}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{uv}$
\end_inset

 are (rectangular) matrices of the 3D total correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 and 3D direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

, both unknowns of the equation.
 The superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 label the solute and the solvent, respectively.
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 enumerate the solvent site interacting with the whole solute.
 In Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

), the solvent is represented by its (square symmetric) susceptibility matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{v}=\omega^{v}+\rho h^{vv}$
\end_inset

 and could be obtained self-consistently from the pure solvent 1D-RISM equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "book:Hirata03,Kovalenko99b"

\end_inset

.
 In practice one operates with the dimensionless Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}^{v}(k)$
\end_inset

 of the solvent susceptibility.
 The low 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}_{\alpha\gamma}^{v}(0)=\rho\kappa/\beta$
\end_inset

 encodes the solvent compressibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and the next leading 
\begin_inset Formula $o(k^{2})$
\end_inset

 terms corrected by DRISM control the dielectric response of the solvent
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perkyns92"

\end_inset

.
 As usual 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/T$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to 1D-RISM case, the closure relation is needed to render the Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

) solvable.
 In this paper, the Kovalenko and Hirata (KH) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

 closure is used, which reads 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}=f(-\beta u_{\alpha}+h_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\exp(x)-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 is the interaction potential between solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the solute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the excess chemical potential of solvation could be analytically
 derived from distribution functions.
 For HNC closure, it has the following form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Singer85"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\mu=\frac{\rho}{\beta}\int\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N_{\text{v}}}\left[|h_{\alpha}|^{2}/2-c_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}h_{\alpha}/2\right]d^{3}r
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and in the corresponding expression for the KH closure the 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}$
\end_inset

-terms contribute only in the depletion regions where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}<0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

.
 This expression, together with a linear convolution relation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

), between the total and direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 leads to seriously overestimated cavity formation energies.
 Indeed, by assuming a simple liquid exposed to a potential sufficiently
 repulsive within an extended volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 and approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $h\approx-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\approx-z^{-1}$
\end_inset

 within the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

, by way of the convolution relation and using a short hand notation 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\rho\kappa/\beta$
\end_inset

 for the compressibility factor, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\Delta\mu\approx\rho V_{0}(z^{-1}+1)/2$
\end_inset

.
 Water is nearly incompressible --- the corresponding compressibility factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx1/16$
\end_inset

 at normal conditions; RISM theories predict comparable numbers depending
 on the closure and water model.
 
