\begin_layout Standard
The PMV correction term is based on the “universal correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (UC) term for 3D-RISM proposed by Palmer et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Palmer10"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\mu^{\text{UC}}=\Delta\mu+a\rho V_{\text{u}}+b\label{eq:3DRISM-UC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Instead of fitting the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, here the correction coefficients are chosen following the strategy of
 Sergiievskyi et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sergiievskyi14"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $a=(2\beta)^{-1}\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N_{\text{v}}}\rho_{\alpha}\tilde{c}_{\alpha}(k=0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c}_{\alpha}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the Fourier representation of direct correlation function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the number density for solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The dimensionless PMV of solute 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho V_{\text{u}}=(\rho\kappa/\beta)\left(1-\rho\int\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N_{\text{v}}}c_{\alpha}(\vec{r})d^{3}r\right)$
\end_inset

 could be obtained from the standard expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "book:Hirata03,Palmer10"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interaction between QM solute and RISM solvent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the 3D-RISM-MM theory, the interaction potential between solvent site
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and QM solute could also be defined as the sum of two parts: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}=u_{\alpha}^{\text{C}}+u_{\alpha}^{\text{LJ}}$
\end_inset

.
 The Lennard-Jones (LJ) type potential term 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}^{\text{LJ}}(r)=4\sum_{i=1}^{N_{u}}\epsilon_{i\alpha}\left[(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r)^{12}-(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r)^{6}\right]$
\end_inset

 which accounts for short-range repulsion and dispersion interactions is
 the same with the MM case, while the electrostatic interaction between
 QM solute electron and charged solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\alpha}^{\text{C}}=\sum_{\alpha}\int n_{v}(\vec{r})f_{\alpha}(\vec{r}-\vec{r}')n(\vec{r}')d^{3}rd^{3}r'\label{eq:solute-solvent-interaction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
